metadata.name: stranger's gift #47
metadata.description:
A human being is the most intelligent and ambiguous particle of the vast organism, for we are the only ones who, in addition to maintaining common life, have the ability to harm our world and each other. Like any particle, the individual can only be fully aware of his own existence and path.

You are surrounded by people. On the scale there are over seven billion people around you. Most of them you do not know and will never know. Just as you don't think about every drop in the sea, you don't think about the existence of each individual person. A person is not in your own world until he/she/they etc. touches it. But, just as in the current of the sea you may come across a sharp stone or the most beautiful pearl, so in the mass of people you may come across that stranger.
He is a constant variable. You can't recognize him among the faceless landscape until he stands at the edge of your world. At the same time, his figure is sacred and not accidental. You were meant to meet him, and he was meant to meet you.
The Stranger has a gift for you. He can show you what the future holds, or answer questions that have long tormented you. 
This moment is a second before you meet your personal stranger.
Where will you meet him? Will he scare you or charm you? What gift will he give you and why? What will he predict for you?
This will be your personal story. Whether you want to tell it or keep it to yourself is up to you.


Code by PureSpider

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #153
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: Suspension #92
metadata.description:
Suspension uses simple objects to create structures suspended in space, held together by relation and composition.

The unique composition algorithm is random enough to produce infinite variations, but ordered enough to produce engaging artworks that are instantly recognizable.

Suspension uses negative space, additive coloring, and a unique rendering technique to create a very distinct style. 

It has many hand tuned palettes, with rare palettes that produce incisive variations.

Suspension is responsive and will render fast at any resolution. It looks great on wide screens of 2K, 4K or larger.

To accommodate the variation in displays, you can use the up/down arrow keys to adjust the brightness. 'r' resets to the default values.

's' will save an image in the exact size of the window, so you can create images in any resolution.

metadata.name: The Tiny Seed #120
metadata.description:
Biological and inorganic matter often grow from a tiny seed. After leaving the seed, the trunk unfurls into an array of possibilities. After some time has passed, the seed is reborn.

Some seeds can take longer to grow than others. All seeds begin in the middle.

A couple resolutions: 256, 512, 1024, 2048 (larger is rarer)
All other parameters change the behavior, colorization, and animation of each piece.
This is a larger edition, since the parameter space is very wide.

Each piece is lightly interactive. During growth, more seeds can be added by clicking and drawing into untraversed territory.

When viewing the piece live, you can press the 's' key to take a capture. Captures may be scaled to any desired resolution using 'nearest-neighbor' scaling.

Made with p5.js, p5Fbo.js, and glsl

metadata.name: pang #47
metadata.description:
Within each of us resides an evolutionary history of primal emotions, yet we often spend our lives dulling and controlling these instincts rather than reveling in them. Art is one of the ways we best express those instincts and intuitions â€“ accessing and visualizing their visceral qualities, and releasing our deepest emotions in a way we can share.

pang reflects emotions that take control of our impulses â€“ anguish, euphoria, obsession. By using crayon-like marks, the artworks convey the catharsis felt while drawing with a childlike abandon. To capture what gives such marks true feeling, the works deliberate the intrinsic movements, pressures, and angles shaped by hands in various moods. These qualities and their frenetic meanderings represent the infinite possibilities of where the crayon could go next â€“ if only we could free ourselves from the layers of control we've built.

The contradictions we struggle with are reflected throughout the works:  in the long, methodical, and mathematical path to creation that yields work that looks fast, free and unrehearsed;  through the randomly-informed computer generation of art that feels human;  and by the depiction of long-standing traditional techniques to help display the conceptual range of a young, innovative art movement still establishing its pivotal place in the canon of art. These tensions parallel the work's underlying concept, accentuating the suspicion that a learned fear of emotional expression might just be the source of our own pang. 

Created in p5.js, pang is inspired by the emotional works and processes of later abstract expressionists such as Cy Twombly and Joan Mitchell â€“ as well as contemporary artists like JosÃ© Parla.

Functionality: 
Press â€˜pâ€™ to save as a png. 
Press â€˜bâ€™ to render with (or without) a transparent background.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality.  0 (lowest quality) to 9 (highest quality, 15000 pixels lengthwise).
Press â¬†ï¸ (arrow up) to incrementally increase pixel density.
Press â¬‡ï¸ (arrow down) to incrementally decrease pixel density.
